<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06118114 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06118114 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  FURNISHING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  SEARCHING through antique shops for a mantel clock? They are getting harder tofind because of their popularity. But there are new windup clocks to be had,and they will be tomorrow's antiques.;    The key-wound L. andamp; J.G. StickleyMission Oak clock is a replica of the original made in 1910. The clock ishandcrafted from quartersawn white oak and is finished in a golden lightstain. It has a leaded front window and a solid-brass etched dial. The richgong counts each hour and sounds on the half.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Home  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MANTEL CLOCK WILL AGE WELL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  What's New  </MEMO><TEXT>     Because you will want to pass this timepiece down to your children, theclock is signed, dated and has a Mission brass label affixed to it. It has aneight-day movement and is 22 inches high.;    Truly gorgeous, the Stickley is$749, plus $75 shipping and insurance through Hammacher Schlemmer, (800)543-3366.;    Pieces of antiquity;    Throw out your ceramic bird collection.Antiquity repros -- from Museum Collection in Boston -- are not only startlingin their classical beauty, but they will teach you and your children a bitabout ancient history.;    One such piece is the oinochoe, a pitcher used inGreece, circa 625 BC. The pitcher is decorated with 22 animal figures aroundits bands ($130). The Traverine Ruin ($145) is a miniature Roman ruin made ofnatural red traverine stone. There are several busts in the collection aswell, and these can be used in both traditional and ultramodern rooms. TheBust of Poseidon, for instance, is 11 inches high and made of bronze ($98).;   For more information, get the Museum Collections catalog by calling (800)442-2460.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  RON GASBARRO, Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910427 